<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910722-0114</DOCNO><DOCID>910722-0114.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Group Aids   Korean Police   In Software Raid   ----   By Damon Darlin   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LOTS MSFT TATE</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)FAR EAST (FE)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)SOUTH KOREA (SK)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   SEOUL, South Korea -- A U.S. personal-computer softwareindustry group said it aided police in making raids on Koreancompanies making or using copied software.   Police attention was focused on shops that allegedly turnout &quot;pirated&quot; computer software, a widespread, but open,practice in Korea. Shops can supply the latest software, aswell as user's manuals, and provide thick catalogs of titlesthey have available. Such practices are illegal in Korea butthe law is rarely enforced.</LP><TEXT>   The Business Software Alliance, the industry group, saidit assisted police in raids July 4 on two large softwareretailers that allegedly produced pirated software. Policeraided Prime Computer in Songtan, a town near Seoul, andComputer Tech, a well-known store in the Itaewon shoppingdistrict of Seoul.   The industry group said police confiscated about 10,000copies of software containing about 4,600 computer programs.They also took 4,200 suspected pirated software manuals and11 personal computers that were allegedly used for thecopying. Two people were also arrested but were not detainedby police, the group said.   The Business Software Alliance also said it filed acriminal complaint against Pacific Fashion Co. of Seoul forallegedly using copied versions of Ashton-Tate Co., MicrosoftInc. and Lotus Development Corp. software. Police raidedPacific Fashion July 12 and allegedly found unauthorizedcopies of software. It is against Korean law to use piratedsoftware, but the practice is widespread.   It was the third raid on a Korean company coordinated bythe industry group. In May, Dae Lim Motorcycle Marketing andSales Co. and Tae Young Industrial Co. were accused of usingunauthorized copies of five manufactures' software. Thosecases are still pending.   The alliance said it is distributing free copies of aKorean language computer program that will audit software ina computer to determine whether the software is original orcopied.</TEXT></DOC>